### Describe the bug
When using WebApplication.MapGet(...).WithGroupName("MY_GROUP"), odd behaviors occur.

On an older version of my package libraries, I was able to produce the behavior in which adding a GroupName to one endpoint in a group adds the GroupName to _all_ of the endpoints in the group, however, that seems to have been fixed as of:
* Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi@8.0.7
* Asp.Versioning.Http@8.1.0
* Asp.Versioning.Mvc.ApiExplorer@8.1.0
* Swashbuckle.AspNetCore@6.7.0

There is still a reproducible bug when you mix and match groups and non-groups with versioning -- If you have a group with a versionSet, and you give one single endpoint of that VersionSet a group name, then all ungrouped and/or unversioned endpoints have the same group name.

For example, with the following code: 
```csharp
var versionSet = 
    app
        .NewApiVersionSet()
        .HasApiVersion(1.0)
        .HasApiVersion(1.1)
        .ReportApiVersions()
        .Build();

app.MapGet(string.Empty, () => "Hello World");
var group = app.MapGroup("api/v{version:apiVersion}");
group.MapGet(string.Empty, () => "Hello World!").WithApiVersionSet(versionSet).MapToApiVersion(1.0);
group.MapGet(string.Empty, () => "Hello World!").WithGroupName("highlander").WithApiVersionSet(versionSet).MapToApiVersion(1.0);
```
one would expect that there is only one endpoint part of the highlander group, but when you look at the swagger.json that is produced:

